        "Wikipedia",
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cato%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The village’s roots lie in the Central New York Military Tract, set aside after the Revolution to reward veterans.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6,
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2",
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/cato_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Southern Central Railroad’s 1872 arrival turned Cato into a grain and fruit shipping hub.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/cato_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Cato covers about one square mile of flat farmland just 25 miles northwest of Syracuse, near the historic Erie Canal path.",
